      "createdAt": "2026-06-12T03:14:02.02841+00:00",
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, I'm really glad you brought this up — two weeks of sharp knee pain is absolutely worth taking seriously, and it makes sense you're looking for answers.\n\nI have to be straight with you here: diagnosing what's causing that pain, or advising on medication like ibuprofen, is genuinely outside my lane as a running coach. I'd be doing you a disservice if I guessed — knee pain that's sharp, that started after a specific run, and that's been hanging around for two weeks deserves a proper assessment from a sports medicine physician or physiotherapist. They can actually examine what's going on and give you a real answer.\n\nA couple of things I'd flag for that appointment: the sharp pain on stairs is worth mentioning specifically, as is your history of IT band tightness from last year. That context could be useful for them.\n\n---\n\nOn your question about continuing to run — I'd gently pump the brakes on that, even with shortened runs, until you've had it looked at. Here's why: running through pain we don't understand can sometimes turn a short-term issue into a longer one, and that would put your July half marathon at much greater risk than a week or two of rest now would. Stepping back right now isn't losing fitness — it's protecting the goal.\n\n**What IS in my coaching scope:** once you have clearance and a clearer picture from a professional, I can adjust your training plan to bring you back sensibly — protecting your July race goal while respecting whatever the clinician recommends. You have time. The race is July 11th, and that's a real asset right now.\n\n---\n\nCan I ask — do you have access to a physio or sports medicine doctor you could get in to see this week? That's the most important next step, and I want to make sure you have a path to get there."
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01N2Qecm1Hgx4Ao9TWHQu75J"
    }
  ],
